            <fr:title text="Cooperative Thread Array (CTA)">Cooperative Thread Array (CTA)</fr:title>
            <fr:meta name="author">false</fr:meta>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <html:p>NVIDIA's hardware-level term for what CUDA programmers call a thread block.</html:p>
            <html:p>A CTA is a group of threads that execute on the same Streaming Multiprocessor (SM), can synchronize via barriers (<html:code>__syncthreads()</html:code>), and share fast on-chip <html:em>shared memory</html:em> (<fr:link href="/8GZN/" title="Shared memory (GPU)" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/8GZN/" display-uri="8GZN" type="local">Shared memory (GPU)</fr:link>). Threads within a CTA are scheduled and executed in groups of 32 called <fr:link href="/OGCS5/" title="Warp (GPU)" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/OGCS5/" display-uri="OGCS5" type="local">warps</fr:link>. </html:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
